			<!-- project 1 -->
			<div id="proj1">
				<div class="block"></div>
				<p class="h">Sol: an interactive map of campus events</p>
				<div class="block"></div>
				<div class="row">
					<div class="box no-left center">
						<img class="screenshot" src="/webapp/sol1.png" />
					</div>
					<p class="t center">
						I am currently working with my friend on a website to
						improve campus life. Users will be able to see, create,
						and join the events on campus. We are using Flutter for
						the front-end, Go (Echo framework) for the back-end, and
						MongoDB for the database. I set up our own tile server
						to display a customized map.
					</p>
					<div class="box no-right center">
						<img class="screenshot" src="/webapp/sol2.png" />
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
			<!-- project 2 -->
			<div id="proj2">
				<div class="block"></div>
				<p class="h">
					Personal diary: web app with note-taking and mood-tracking
					features
				</p>
				<div class="block"></div>
				<div class="box" style="margin: 45px; margin-top: 0">
					<div class="gif-frame">
						<img class="gif" src="/webapp/Organizer Gif.gif" />
					</div>
				</div>
				<p class="t">
					As part of my IB Computer Science class, I created a
					personalized web app that integrates note-taking and
					mood-tracking functionalities into a seamless personal diary
					experience.
				</p>
				<div class="block"></div>
				<details class="spoiler">
					<summary class="h">Details</summary>
					<div class="block"></div>
					<p class="t">
						The front-end of the web app is built using React
						(including Recharts for data visualization), providing a
						responsive and intuitive user interface. On the backend,
						Express.js handles the server-side operations and
						Mongoose controls storing and retrieving data from the
						MongoDB database.
					</p>
					<div class="block"></div>
					<div class="row gallery" style="gap: 45px">
						<img class="gallery-img" src="/webapp/Flowchart1.png" />
						<img class="gallery-img" src="/webapp/Flowchart2.png" />
						<img
							class="gallery-img"
							src="/webapp/MigrationChart.png"
						/>
					</div>
					<div class="block"></div>
					<p class="t">
						I adhered to the principles of the engineering design
						process. From researching the problem and specifying
						design requirements to the preliminary design and user
						testing, each step was a deliberate and iterative
						progression. An example is the script to migrate
						existing notes from Google Keep included after user
						feedback to streamline the transition process.
					</p>
				</details>
			</div>
			<div class="block"></div>

			<hr />
			<!-- project 3 -->
			<div id="proj3">
				<div class="block"></div>
				<p class="h">
					Device for teaching handwriting to blind and visually
					impaired learners
				</p>
				<div class="block"></div>
				<div class="row">
					<div class="block"></div>
					<div class="box center no-right">
						<p class="t">
							A device that autonomously teaches handwriting to
							blind and visually impaired learners. I used G-code
							to program the movement of a mechanism based on
							CNC-routers and JavaScript for voice user interface.
						</p>
					</div>
					<img class="gallery-img" src="/webapp/jazgysh.jpg" />
				</div>
				<div class="block"></div>
				<details class="spoiler">
					<summary class="h">Details</summary>
					<div class="block"></div>
					<div style="padding-right: 45px">
						<img
							style="width: 100%"
							src="/webapp/JazgyshScheme.png"
						/>
						<div class="block"></div>
					</div>
					<p class="t">
						Jazgysh is a solution for empowering the blind and
						visually impaired to learn handwriting autonomously. The
						project unfolded in several stages, beginning with
						in-depth research on the educational challenges faced by
						visually impaired and blind learners, as well as the
						existing solutions. We then formulated a novel teaching
						method, implemented the necessary hardware and software
						using Computer Numerical Control (CNC) router
						technology.
						<br />
						<br />
						I wrote instructions for the pen movement using G-code and
						a voice user interface using JavaScript to integrate tactile
						and audial feedback that enhances users’ motor skills. The
						research culminated in a cost-effective (~$100), unique alternative
						for handwriting education, proven effective through a two-stage
						experiment. Jazgysh is a versatile, affordable tool suitable
						for individuals or groups of various ages, requiring minimal
						external assistance.
					</p>
				</details>
			</div>
			<div class="block"></div>

			<hr />
			<!-- project 4 -->
			<div id="proj4">
				<div class="block"></div>
				<p class="h">Rando: mobile app for randonauting</p>
				<div class="block"></div>
				<div class="row">
					<p class="t">
						I developed an app for randonauting: generating random
						geographic coordinates and then exploring the area
						associated with those coordinates. The idea is that by
						introducing an element of randomness into the process,
						individuals may experience novel and unexpected
						discoveries, leading to a sense of adventure and
						exploration.
					</p>
					<p class="t">
						I used React Native for the front end, set up Amazon Web
						Services instances (to serve map tiles using
						OpenStreetMap data and to provide routing instructions
						through Open Source Routing Machine). I also used
						trigonometry cartesian coordinates into latitude and
						longitude points.
					</p>
				</div>
				<div class="block"></div>
				<div class="box no-left no-right no-bottom">
					<div class="row" style="justify-content: space-evenly">
						<img class="screenshot" src="/webapp/rando1.png" />
						<img class="screenshot" src="/webapp/rando2.png" />
						<img class="screenshot" src="/webapp/rando3.png" />
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
			<!-- project 5 -->
			<div id="proj5">
				<div class="row">
					<div class="box center no-left" style="flex: 1">
						<p class="h">
							Statistics and data analysis for geography class
							project
						</p>
					</div>
					<div
						class="box no-left no-right"
						style="flex: 2; padding: 45px"
					>
						<img style="width: 100%" src="/webapp/geo2.png" />
					</div>
				</div>
				<img style="width: 100%" src="/webapp/geo1.png" />
				<div class="block"></div>
				<p class="t">
					I conducted an analysis of the urban environment during a
					field trip for my Geography class. Focusing on key
					parameters such as noise levels, congestion, and built
					environment quality, the project aimed to provide insights
					into spatial inequality in terms of infrastructure and
					living conditions between the neighborhoods of varying
					affluence along one of the main avenues of the city.
					Although it was not required for the class, I used the
					Plotly library for Python for visualizations and NumPy,
					Pandas, and SciPy for data manipulation.
				</p>
				<div class="block"></div>
			</div>
		</div>

